But let's go ahead
and bring Lauren up.

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:48.820
Thank you.

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:55.259
This is exciting.

00:00:55.259 --> 00:00:56.675
LAUREN EPSHTEYN:
Thank you, Seema.

00:00:56.675 --> 00:00:58.850
Thank you for interviewing
me today and hosting.

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:01.140
I asked Seema to
interview me in front

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:03.510
of so many of my
close Google friends

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:06.070
because she is fantastic
at doing exactly that.

00:01:06.070 --> 00:01:08.700
She's hosted many
panels at Google before,

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:10.950
so thank you for your time
today, and thank all of you

00:01:10.950 --> 00:01:11.860
for coming.

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.401
It means the world to me that
you would come, and some of you

00:01:14.401 --> 00:01:16.036
are participating today.

00:01:16.036 --> 00:01:18.160
I know just about all of
you, but thank you so much

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:19.690
for your time.

00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:21.920
SEEMA VASHI: So
let's kick it off.

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:23.910
We all know why we're
here for this book,

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:25.875
and you wrote this book.

00:01:25.875 --> 00:01:27.750
Can you talk a little
bit about what prompted

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:30.470
you to even go on this journey?

00:01:30.470 --> 00:01:33.200
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: So I've
always loved writing.

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.580
I'm a big believer
in if you want

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:36.497
to figure out what
you're passionate about

00:01:36.497 --> 00:01:38.580
or realize what you're
passionate about, look back

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.170
to what you had
fun doing as a kid.

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:43.620
And for me, writing stories was
absolutely one of those things

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:45.530
that I loved doing as a kid.

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:47.040
I remember when I
was 10 years old,

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:49.780
we had a family reunion that
had a questionnaire that said,

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:51.160
what's your life goal?

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:52.710
Or what do you hope
you do someday?

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:55.168
And at 10 years old I said, I
want to be a "New York Times"

00:01:55.168 --> 00:01:56.002
best-selling author.

00:01:56.002 --> 00:01:58.459
I don't even know how I knew
what that was at 10 years old,

00:01:58.459 --> 00:01:59.849
but that's what I wanted to do.

00:01:59.849 --> 00:02:01.640
So I'm not sure that
"A Northern Gentleman"

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:03.620
is going to achieve
that goal for me,

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:05.850
but when the story
came to me, I had

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:09.889
to at least give it a try-- try
writing fiction as an adult.

00:02:09.889 --> 00:02:12.460
SEEMA VASHI: And so
going about this,

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:14.269
how did you know
how to write a book?

00:02:14.269 --> 00:02:15.560
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Good question.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.074
So they say that readers
make the best writers.

00:02:18.074 --> 00:02:20.240
Although, I was thinking
about it this morning-- no,

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:23.719
they say drinkers
make the best writers.

00:02:23.719 --> 00:02:25.510
But they say readers
make the best writers,

00:02:25.510 --> 00:02:28.704
and I have always been a
voracious reader, maybe not

00:02:28.704 --> 00:02:31.120
as much as-- I know there's
actually a lot of Googlers who

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:33.540
read much more than I do,
and I'm inspired by you all.

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:37.000
But hopefully, then, you
can relate to this idea.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.590
I personally have always loved
American historical fiction

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:40.810
perhaps the most.

00:02:40.810 --> 00:02:43.872
Some of my favorite
books are by Gore Vidal,

00:02:43.872 --> 00:02:45.610
or there's one in
particular that I loved

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:47.040
by an author named Jack Finney.

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:49.680
Does anybody know
"Time and Again"?

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:52.460
It's a great book,
where a guy who's

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:57.310
living in New York in the
year 1970 time travels back,

00:02:57.310 --> 00:02:59.150
so there's a little
tiny bit of sci-fi

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.710
there, to New York in 1882.

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:05.870
And as I was researching
for America in the 1890s,

00:03:05.870 --> 00:03:08.677
it was definitely
influential in understanding

00:03:08.677 --> 00:03:11.260
what types of words that people
used, what types of activities

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:15.710
did people do in the 1800s and
late 1800s, so I love that.

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:17.370
I read a lot.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:19.980
I also read a book
on how to write.

00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:21.010
I read several.

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:23.930
One in particular, if anyone is
interested in writing a fiction

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:27.100
book, was by a literary
agent and editor named

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.850
Sol Stein called
"On Writing," and I

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:30.540
found that one really helpful.

00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:32.540
The biggest takeaway
I had from that book

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:34.350
was that you need
to raise the stakes.

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:36.710
People will only be
interested in what you're

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:39.750
writing if they feel like
there's something big at stake,

00:03:39.750 --> 00:03:43.020
whether it's someone's
life, or his classic example

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:44.790
is make it the
fate of the earth.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.040
Is there an asteroid coming?

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:48.660
That wasn't as applicable
in a story like "A Northern

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.650
Gentleman," but I tried, when
possible, to raise the stakes.

00:03:52.650 --> 00:03:55.510
And then my favorite
book on writing

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:56.960
is actually one
by a screenwriter.

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.770
Has anyone heard of the
book called "Save the Cat?"

00:03:59.770 --> 00:04:00.560
Yeah, someone has.

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:02.030
Have you read it?

00:04:02.030 --> 00:04:03.630
OK, so yeah, "Save
the Cat" is a book

00:04:03.630 --> 00:04:07.000
on screenwriting, where
the "namesake rule," one

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.170
of his first rules of
writing, is that you have

00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:11.690
to make the character likeable.

00:04:11.690 --> 00:04:14.110
So early on, have
the main character

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.570
do something small
but very likable,

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:19.149
like saving a cat that's
stuck up in a tree.

00:04:19.149 --> 00:04:22.410
So I tried after
reading that to make

00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:25.077
Drucker, my main character,
do small little things,

00:04:25.077 --> 00:04:26.660
whether it was
standing up for himself

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:29.760
or saying something clever back
to someone, that would make you

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:31.040
like him and root for him.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:34.442
Rather than, actually, the very
initial version of Drucker, he

00:04:34.442 --> 00:04:35.730
was a little pathetic.

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:37.320
He hated his job, which he does.

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:38.986
And if you read the
book, you'll know he

00:04:38.986 --> 00:04:40.480
hates his job in the beginning.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.600
But he was sort of
beaten down by it.

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:47.064
And then reading "Save the Cat"
really made him more empowered.

00:04:47.064 --> 00:04:48.730
And then, finally,
if anyone else really

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:51.759
wants to write a book, the
thing I did when I started was I

00:04:51.759 --> 00:04:52.300
took a class.

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:54.980
It was a four-month class at
Media Bistro, a couple hundred

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:57.650
bucks, and you stay accountable
for bringing your homework

00:04:57.650 --> 00:04:58.840
every week.

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.220
And I did that for about
four months, and the takeaway

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:03.970
I had from that class--
it was fun to just

00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:05.219
have others read your writing.

00:05:05.219 --> 00:05:08.000
They gave me some good ideas.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.970
They reminded me
that when you're

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:13.370
writing historical
fiction in particular,

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:15.750
the author knows things
that have actually

00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:17.670
happened that the
characters don't, and so I

00:05:17.670 --> 00:05:19.030
had a lot of fun with that.

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:21.113
There's one point, and I
won't give too much away,

00:05:21.113 --> 00:05:23.270
where Drucker, the
main character,

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:26.110
suggests the idea of
something like a credit card.

00:05:26.110 --> 00:05:28.170
And the people around
him think he's nuts.

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:28.870
You know, what?

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:29.970
That sounds horrible.

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:31.390
That will never work.

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:33.509
Because if you think
about it, in the 1890s,

00:05:33.509 --> 00:05:35.800
that probably would have
sounded like a really bad idea

00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:38.290
to someone who just had
a local credit account

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:40.562
with the local merchant.

00:05:40.562 --> 00:05:42.520
So I had a lot of fun
with that, and that class

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.305
was really useful in that way.

00:05:44.305 --> 00:05:45.180
SEEMA VASHI: Awesome.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:48.750
So I think a lot of people
here, as well as myself, love

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:51.920
the idea of writing a book.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:54.846
And you have a full time job.

00:05:54.846 --> 00:05:55.970
When did you find the time?

00:05:55.970 --> 00:05:57.710
When did you actually
get this done?

00:05:57.710 --> 00:05:58.690
How long did it take?

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:00.010
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: I get
that question all the time.

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:02.470
And I wish that I had
a really clean answer,

00:06:02.470 --> 00:06:04.912
like Tuesdays and Thursdays
from 6:00 to 9:00.

00:06:04.912 --> 00:06:06.870
Like for some of my NYU
friends, you could just

00:06:06.870 --> 00:06:09.145
have an easy answer for that.

00:06:09.145 --> 00:06:10.270
It wasn't like that at all.

00:06:10.270 --> 00:06:11.650
For me, it was sporadic.

00:06:11.650 --> 00:06:13.660
And I say this
because if you have

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:15.489
a passion or a story
or an art project

00:06:15.489 --> 00:06:18.030
or whatever it is that you think
you don't have the time for,

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:19.810
I hope that me sitting
up here is proof

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:21.710
that you don't need a
whole lot of free time

00:06:21.710 --> 00:06:23.870
in order to make some
forward progress.

00:06:23.870 --> 00:06:26.920
Sometimes I would challenge
myself to do 100 words a day,

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.640
usually in May, because that
rhymed-- 100 words a day

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:30.317
in May.

00:06:30.317 --> 00:06:31.900
And then in June, I
wouldn't touch it.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:35.330
And some days 500 words
would flow easily,

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:37.905
and other days getting to 99
would be a real challenge.

00:06:37.905 --> 00:06:39.655
And then, like I said,
I wouldn't touch it

00:06:39.655 --> 00:06:40.999
for the next month.

00:06:40.999 --> 00:06:43.040
And actually, I put the
book down for four years.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:45.110
I didn't touch it for
four years after writing

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:46.676
for an initial nine months.

00:06:46.676 --> 00:06:48.300
And when I picked it
back up, the story

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:50.264
just came right back to me.

00:06:50.264 --> 00:06:51.430
It was there waiting for me.

00:06:51.430 --> 00:06:53.842
So that's why I knew I
had to keep going with it.

00:06:53.842 --> 00:06:55.800
Why I say, again, to all
of you in the audience

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:58.840
and you watching, you don't
need a whole lot of free time

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:02.270
just to make some progress
on a story or a project that

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:03.460
means something to you.

00:07:03.460 --> 00:07:04.910
SEEMA VASHI: So what
was that timeline, then?

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:06.310
So you said you worked
on it for nine months.

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:08.143
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Yep,
so, yep, I started it.

00:07:08.143 --> 00:07:11.130
I had moved to New
York summer 2007.

00:07:11.130 --> 00:07:14.330
One year later, I got this
idea while sitting on a train

00:07:14.330 --> 00:07:15.252
back from DC.

00:07:15.252 --> 00:07:17.460
For any of you haven't read
the book yet, a lot of it

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:18.690
takes place on a train.

00:07:18.690 --> 00:07:21.430
Train travel's a big
part of the book.

00:07:21.430 --> 00:07:23.410
The idea came to
me first, actually;

00:07:23.410 --> 00:07:24.804
I was playing
around with titles,

00:07:24.804 --> 00:07:26.470
and I thought of "a
northern gentleman."

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:27.640
That just sounded
interesting to me.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:28.720
And I thought, what
would that be about?

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.303
Well, definitely a
guy from the South,

00:07:30.303 --> 00:07:32.660
and that's where I started.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:35.190
And then I signed up for this
Media Bistro writing class,

00:07:35.190 --> 00:07:38.700
took that for four months,
wrote for about the next five

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:42.022
after that, but then really put
it down and didn't touch it,

00:07:42.022 --> 00:07:44.230
didn't have the time, had
a lot of other distractions

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:46.230
in my life for the
next four years.

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:48.490
And then when I graduated
from business school

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:50.980
in the spring of 2013 was
when I really picked it up.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:53.910
And, you know, I can't say that
I had the Tuesday and Thursday

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:55.690
nights, three hours
at a time, but that's

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:57.330
when I really started
making the time,

00:07:57.330 --> 00:07:58.600
even though it was sporadic.

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:01.142
SEEMA VASHI: And was this like
an internal goal for yourself,

00:08:01.142 --> 00:08:02.516
or did you have
other people kind

00:08:02.516 --> 00:08:03.699
of keeping you accountable?

00:08:03.699 --> 00:08:04.740
I guess the class helped.

00:08:04.740 --> 00:08:05.800
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: The class
helped, but that was only

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:06.890
in the beginning.

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:07.660
It was for me.

00:08:07.660 --> 00:08:09.420
I had this story, and
I wanted to tell it.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.980
And every time I came back to
it, it was still there for me,

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:13.630
and it was exciting and fun.

00:08:13.630 --> 00:08:16.530
So it was really just for me
and holding it in my hand,

00:08:16.530 --> 00:08:18.090
and having control
over the story

00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:21.197
and the process was a
really good experience.

00:08:21.197 --> 00:08:22.280
SEEMA VASHI: That's great.

00:08:22.280 --> 00:08:24.750
So everyone here knows
that Lauren's name

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:27.330
is Lauren, not Lane.

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:30.840
So on the cover of the book you
see that she uses a pen name.

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:31.770
It's Lane Everett.

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:34.201
So could you explain why you
did that-- same initials?

00:08:34.201 --> 00:08:35.950
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Yes,
this is the question

00:08:35.950 --> 00:08:37.919
I get the second most
after, how did you ever

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:39.350
find the time to do that?

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:40.490
Yes, I used a pen name.

00:08:40.490 --> 00:08:42.940
I always wanted
to use a pen name.

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:45.770
It sounds a little bit
shallow or on the surface,

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:47.760
but I wanted something
unisex and All-American

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:48.843
on the cover of this book.

00:08:48.843 --> 00:08:51.585
To me, this was like
an American story,

00:08:51.585 --> 00:08:53.710
and I wanted something that
could have been written

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:56.670
by any classic American name.

00:08:56.670 --> 00:08:57.820
So I wanted that.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:08:59.480
But also-- and I
hope you guys can all

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:01.620
relate to this,
many of you being

00:09:01.620 --> 00:09:05.927
in sales and engineering-- but
I am in client meetings a lot.

00:09:05.927 --> 00:09:08.010
I didn't know who was going
to be saying something

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:10.426
about this book or another
book that I write in the future

00:09:10.426 --> 00:09:13.084
and what they would be saying,
and I didn't want a client

00:09:13.084 --> 00:09:15.000
googling "who just gave
me that advice on what

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.585
to do with my mobile strategy"
and finding something untoward

00:09:17.585 --> 00:09:19.460
that someone would have
written about Drucker

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:21.810
or any other of my characters.

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:24.469
So I wanted to keep
that nice and separate,

00:09:24.469 --> 00:09:25.510
really draw a line there.

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:27.580
And I know that sounds
clean in principle.

00:09:27.580 --> 00:09:29.560
But I have to tell you, and
I think this is interesting,

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:30.810
I've been, in the
last couple months,

00:09:30.810 --> 00:09:33.080
talking to everyone I can
find with some connection

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:34.755
to the book marketing industry.

00:09:34.755 --> 00:09:37.130
And to a T, just about every
single one of them has said,

00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:39.060
no, you need to republish
using your own name.

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:40.410
Why?

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:43.150
Because I know there are
many authors who historically

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:44.020
have used pen names.

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:45.220
There's some famous ones.

00:09:45.220 --> 00:09:47.840
One of my favorite is
Ayn Rand, or Ayn Rand.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:50.640
Her name was Alisa
Rosenbaum or something.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:53.100
So many historical
authors did that.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:56.049
But these days,
apparently, and so I hear,

00:09:56.049 --> 00:09:57.340
it's not books that sell books.

00:09:57.340 --> 00:09:59.250
It's authors that sell books.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:01.160
And in this world
of social media,

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:03.740
it's really hard to
fake an identity.

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:05.350
And as I'm saying
these words, I'm

00:10:05.350 --> 00:10:07.850
laughing to myself because I'm
like that's what Drucker did.

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:11.559
That's why it's so fun to
live vicariously through him

00:10:11.559 --> 00:10:14.100
because he lived in this time
when you could fake an identity

00:10:14.100 --> 00:10:15.404
and just start over again.

00:10:15.404 --> 00:10:16.570
SEEMA VASHI: That's so cool.

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:17.450
LAUREN EPSHTEYN:
Yeah, so we'll see.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:20.110
Right now, I'm keeping Lane
Everett, and I'm happy with it.

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:22.380
And, in fact, we're
launching-- we're launching?

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:24.840
I'm launching the book
to the public November 15

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:25.590
with Lane Everett.

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.090
If you pick up this
book now, you'll

00:10:27.090 --> 00:10:29.300
see on the page it
says LE Everett inside.

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:31.040
That makes it a
classic first edition

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:34.080
copy, because as
of November 15th,

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:35.700
it'll actually say Lane Everett.

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:38.320
I decided to go full
forward movement

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:40.180
with Lane Everett for now.

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:41.560
SEEMA VASHI: And how did you
come up with Lane Everett?

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:42.900
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: I wish
I had a good story.

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:44.316
That one, there
truly is no story.

00:10:44.316 --> 00:10:46.710
I just like it, and it has
LE like Lauren Epshteyn.

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:49.132
SEEMA VASHI: Did you want Lane
to be like could be a man,

00:10:49.132 --> 00:10:49.840
could be a woman?

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.839
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Yes, I
wanted something unisex.

00:10:51.839 --> 00:10:55.170
And, again, to a T, the couple
of people who have said,

00:10:55.170 --> 00:10:56.732
that is not unisex--
each one of them

00:10:56.732 --> 00:10:59.190
has a different version of what
Lane absolutely is to them.

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:00.689
Some people said,
Lane's not unisex.

00:11:00.689 --> 00:11:02.330
That's just a man's name.

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:04.740
Others have said, Lane-- I
know only know women Lanes.

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:06.362
So I think that
makes it very unisex.

00:11:06.362 --> 00:11:07.070
SEEMA VASHI: Yes.

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:09.450
And what does it mean to
be launching to the public?

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:10.325
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Aha!

00:11:10.325 --> 00:11:12.650
So you all received
notice of this book

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:14.980
while it was in the friends
and family marketing phase.

00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:17.112
And actually, the
beauty of that was

00:11:17.112 --> 00:11:18.570
that I caught a
few things I wanted

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:20.690
to change-- not plot
wise, not structurally,

00:11:20.690 --> 00:11:23.780
just a couple of formatting
things that I wanted to change.

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:26.900
And so, took it down
for three weeks.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:30.220
I'm launching to the public
November 15th with some AdWords

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:35.330
campaigns and some PR and
some more in-person events.

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:37.870
SEEMA VASHI: Awesome,
that's great.

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:39.952
Cool, so now I think
now would be-- I mean,

00:11:39.952 --> 00:11:41.910
people here know a little
bit of the background

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:43.210
of why you wrote the book.

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:45.060
Why don't we hear from the book?

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:46.840
You want to read
a chapter from it?

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:48.756
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: Yes, I
would love to do that.

00:11:48.756 --> 00:11:50.699
So I'm going to read
you all Chapter 3,

00:11:50.699 --> 00:11:52.240
because in this
chapter you're really

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:53.948
introduced to the main
character, Drucker

00:11:53.948 --> 00:11:55.660
May, and some of the
struggles that he's

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:58.227
going through with
his father, who

00:11:58.227 --> 00:11:59.810
is the president of
the bank and wants

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:02.226
Drucker to be president of the
bank, which Drucker doesn't

00:12:02.226 --> 00:12:03.060
want.

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:05.580
Drucker's struggling
with his boredom at work.

00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:08.760
And this is the point where he
really comes to the realization

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:10.360
that if you're unhappy
with something,

00:12:10.360 --> 00:12:13.730
it's not that hard to
just get up and leave,

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:15.820
or to at least leave your
desk for a few minutes.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:20.480
And people always ask me, how
autobiographical is this book?

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:23.900
And my answer is generally
that the autobiography

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:24.880
was very subtle.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:26.790
There was little tiny moments.

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:29.400
He's going to get up from
his desk in this chapter.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:31.580
And that was inspired
by back in 2008,

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:34.050
back when I was questioning,
I was a year out of college

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:35.591
and wondering, oh,
my god, am I going

00:12:35.591 --> 00:12:38.400
to sit at a desk for the rest
of my life, all day every day?

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:42.110
I would just take one lap
around 76th and 9th Avenue,

00:12:42.110 --> 00:12:44.487
and that made a lot of
difference in the afternoon,

00:12:44.487 --> 00:12:46.070
just getting that
breath of fresh air.

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:48.590
And so I tried to
instill little pieces

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:51.530
of those actions in Drucker.

00:12:51.530 --> 00:12:53.500
Anyway, so Chapter 3,
which I'm about to read,

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:55.958
I think it really introduces
what "A Northern Gentleman" is

00:12:55.958 --> 00:12:57.397
really all about.

00:12:57.397 --> 00:12:58.980
Yes, it's historical
fiction, but it's

00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:01.260
about figuring out what you
want to do with your life

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:02.870
and finding the
courage to do so.

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:04.284
So let's go ahead.

00:13:04.284 --> 00:13:06.200
SEEMA VASHI: I need to
get the Kindle version.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:07.410
LAUREN EPSHTEYN: I have
the Kindle version.

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:09.125
Anyone already read
the Kindle version--

00:13:09.125 --> 00:13:11.000
part of what was going
on with the re-release

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.920
is that Kindle formatted
it a little wrong.

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:17.180
So you'll have noticed a
couple of strange typos

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:18.440
that Amazon inserted.

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:22.720
But, no big deal; you should
have still gotten the idea.

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:25.500
Chapter 3-- "Halfway
through the week

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:28.290
that he been given to think of
a way to save Atlanta Southern

00:13:28.290 --> 00:13:31.180
National Bank from a
swift and ugly collapse,

00:13:31.180 --> 00:13:32.680
Drucker found
himself with nothing

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:35.190
to show for his efforts but
a page full of scribbles

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:36.910
and a pounding headache.

00:13:36.910 --> 00:13:38.580
In those moments when
he wasn't battling

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:41.000
the throbbing in his
temples, he did his best

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.705
not to yield to Hank's
menacing voice in his head.

00:13:43.705 --> 00:13:46.830
"Frankly, I don't even see
why you bother pretending.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:48.890
That board meeting
makes no difference.

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:52.490
Your father will convince them
to vote you in no matter what."

00:13:52.490 --> 00:13:54.210
Every time Drucker
felt himself getting

00:13:54.210 --> 00:13:57.610
close to coming up with some
sort of plan for the bank,

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:01.400
those words would begin to ring
in his ears, distracting him.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:03.960
He heard them again as he
stood next to his desk,

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:07.400
gazing out at the
sunny summer afternoon

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:09.700
on the other side of the
window, feeling guilty

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:11.670
that his efforts thus
far had been fruitless,

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:13.280
but also wondering
if perhaps there

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:15.960
wasn't a part of him
that wanted to fail

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:17.860
at this task he had been given.

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:20.980
After all, if he were to be
struck by a miraculous idea,

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:23.350
he could save face in
front of the board.

00:14:23.350 --> 00:14:24.440
But then what?

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.210
A good showing in that
meeting would only

00:14:26.210 --> 00:14:29.310
add fuel to the fire of his
father's already heated desire

00:14:29.310 --> 00:14:31.690
to install Drucker in his post.

00:14:31.690 --> 00:14:33.370
On the other hand,
if Drucker were

00:14:33.370 --> 00:14:36.730
to show up at the board meeting
empty handed and unprepared,

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:40.200
he would certainly embarrass
both himself and his father.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:43.670
But might a mediocre performance
in front of the board actually

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:45.450
be to his advantage?

00:14:45.450 --> 00:14:47.560
It would certainly
tarnish his image,

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:50.440
perhaps in just the right way.

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:52.560
A disappointing show
at the board meeting

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.590
could heap a little extra
dirt on his already soiled

00:14:55.590 --> 00:14:59.260
reputation, and it could be
just enough to prevent the board

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:02.170
from endorsing the president's
proposal of Drucker

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:04.000
as his successor.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.740
The thought intrigued him, but
Drucker couldn't bring himself

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:09.160
to give up entirely just yet.

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:11.950
The family name was among
a small and dwindling list

00:15:11.950 --> 00:15:14.370
of things that he and
his father shared.

00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:17.580
To sully his own name would
be to drag his father's down

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:20.000
in the dirt, too, and he
couldn't bring himself

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.880
to do that to his father.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:24.140
He couldn't deny
that a part of him

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:27.300
very much wanted to, though,
and the guilt of knowing it

00:15:27.300 --> 00:15:30.620
gave Drucker a suffocating
itch in his lungs.

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:32.760
He felt the desperate
need for fresh air,

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:36.530
and so, very quietly, to avoid
catching anyone's attention,

00:15:36.530 --> 00:15:38.980
he snuck out of the building.

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:41.790
The July day was warm
and drier than usual,

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:43.780
with a light breeze
that smelled alive

00:15:43.780 --> 00:15:46.710
compared to the musty
air inside the bank.

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:48.460
Drucker walked to
the base of the tree

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:51.280
that he had so often gazed
at through the window.

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:53.470
He reached out and
touched the bark

00:15:53.470 --> 00:15:57.060
and was surprised to find that
it was rough, that it was real.

00:15:57.060 --> 00:15:59.150
In his mind, the tree
had become a symbol

00:15:59.150 --> 00:16:01.730
of all that was outside
the bank and therefore

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:03.230
off limits to him.

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:05.650
He'd spent hours,
days even, staring out

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:09.390
the window at the tree, thinking
of how that thin pane of glass

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:12.110
made the tree seem so far away.

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:14.260
Plucking a leaf from
a low hanging branch,

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:16.010
Drucker considered
that it wasn't the fact

00:16:16.010 --> 00:16:18.700
that the tree was real
that was so remarkable,

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:22.690
but rather how easy
it had been to touch.

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:25.930
All he had done was get up
from his desk, walk outside,

00:16:25.930 --> 00:16:28.500
and there it was
waiting for him.

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:30.210
Drucker lowered
himself to the ground,

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:32.380
where he sat leaning
against the tree,

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:34.730
careful to shield himself
with its wide trunk

00:16:34.730 --> 00:16:37.500
so that no one inside the
building could see him.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:40.860
It felt right to be outside
in the fresh air with his back

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:42.480
facing the bank.

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:46.140
A lifetime, a life, could be
sucked away in that office,

00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:49.269
and his would be if
he didn't walk away.

00:16:49.269 --> 00:16:51.060
If he wasn't fired
after the board meeting,

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:53.610
Drucker decided, he
would have to quit.

00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:54.820
But why stop there?

00:16:54.820 --> 00:16:56.540
If you could leave
Atlanta Southern,

00:16:56.540 --> 00:16:58.860
he might as well leave
Atlanta altogether.

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:01.416
He could go North,
perhaps to Boston.

00:17:01.416 --> 00:17:04.270
He'd been 15 when
Lucy's mother had died.

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:06.750
She'd moved back to Boston
to be with her sisters,

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:08.589
and 15 was too old
for a governess,

00:17:08.589 --> 00:17:10.930
his mother had
declared, and so Lucy

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:12.799
had been placed neither
in Drucker's home,

00:17:12.799 --> 00:17:14.790
nor in his heart.

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:16.470
For the first time
in quite a while,

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:18.349
Drucker felt a rush
of excitement course

00:17:18.349 --> 00:17:19.609
through his veins.

00:17:19.609 --> 00:17:22.920
In Atlanta, everyone knew
him before they even met him.

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:25.700
Whether he worked at Atlanta
Southern National Bank or not,

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:28.359
he would be known
as his father's son.

00:17:28.359 --> 00:17:30.120
If he were to go
to Boston though,

00:17:30.120 --> 00:17:32.040
there he could be anybody.

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:34.000
He could be the son
of a banker as easily

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:35.950
as he could be the
son of a farmer,

00:17:35.950 --> 00:17:37.850
if they had farmers in Boston.

00:17:37.850 --> 00:17:39.144
He'd have to check.

00:17:39.144 --> 00:17:40.560
Maybe he would say
that his father

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:43.090
had died on a whaling ship and
left Drucker and his mother

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:44.170
with nothing.

00:17:44.170 --> 00:17:46.420
Or maybe he would say that
he was a descendant of one

00:17:46.420 --> 00:17:48.780
of those men who had
poured tea into the harbor

00:17:48.780 --> 00:17:50.870
or signed the Constitution.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:53.770
Yes, Boston would be
the perfect place.

00:17:53.770 --> 00:17:55.820
He even had the
accent down perfectly

00:17:55.820 --> 00:17:59.150
after years of spending
so much time with Lucy.

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:01.380
As a child, he'd
taken special notice

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:04.720
of the way and words tripped
off her tongue a little faster,

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:07.170
the way she hit
consonants a little harder

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:10.010
than the native-born
Southern ladies he knew.

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:12.110
Often, during their
long afternoons

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:15.160
together, he would switch
into his Northern accent,

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:17.380
changing the pace and
style of his speech

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:19.760
as if he were speaking
another language.

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:21.120
At first, Lucy had laughed.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:23.880
But then she became like the
teacher she had once been,

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:27.290
gently correcting him when
he lapsed for a moment.

00:18:27.290 --> 00:18:30.130
We say "get," not
"git," she'd say.

00:18:30.130 --> 00:18:31.710
Rhymes with "bet."

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:33.920
And Drucker would repeat
after her, quickly

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:38.340
picking up on the distinctly
Northern vernacular.

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:40.520
The happy yelps of children
chasing one another

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:43.150
down Peachtree Street
snapped Drucker back

00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:44.600
to the present moment.

00:18:44.600 --> 00:18:46.750
Two hours must have
passed, he thought,

00:18:46.750 --> 00:18:49.570
as he pushed off the ground
and rose to his feet.

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:52.720
He walked back toward the bank,
which looked different somehow

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:55.520
now that he was taking it in
with the eyes of a man who knew

00:18:55.520 --> 00:18:57.590
he would soon be leaving it.

00:18:57.590 --> 00:19:00.790
As he paced slowly down the
hallway back to his office,

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:03.310
he felt the sturdy clap of
the hand on his shoulder.

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:07.210
Drucker turned to see his father
with Hank trailing behind him

00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:08.842
like a faithful Labrador.

00:19:08.842 --> 00:19:11.145
"There you are," said
the bank's president.

00:19:11.145 --> 00:19:14.266
"I've been looking for you, but
you weren't in your office."

00:19:14.266 --> 00:19:17.070
"I stepped outside,"
said Drucker.

00:19:17.070 --> 00:19:17.930
"Oh?

00:19:17.930 --> 00:19:20.740
asked the president, a bit
surprised, "and what were you

00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:24.390
doing out there?" "I was
just doing some thinking,"

00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:27.040
answered Drucker,
not untruthfully.

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:30.100
The president brightened.
"That's my boy," he beamed.

00:19:30.100 --> 00:19:33.910
"My best business ideas always
congeal when I'm taking a walk.

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:36.172
So you've come up
with a plan, then?"

00:19:36.172 --> 00:19:38.750
"Well, there are still
some details to attend to,"

00:19:38.750 --> 00:19:41.610
said Drucker, thinking of
his recently hatched plan

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:45.360
to leave Atlanta. "Well, by all
means, attend to the details,"

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:47.230
roared the president
with excitement.

00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:48.940
He took a step
closer to Drucker,

00:19:48.940 --> 00:19:51.510
his nose twitching as he
examined his son's face.

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:53.850
"By God, you're close, Drucker.

00:19:53.850 --> 00:19:54.990
I can sense it.

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:58.360
I can always smell a good
idea, and--" he turned his head

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:00.650
and sniffed the air.
"It sure does smell

00:20:00.650 --> 00:20:03.360
like you've got
something juicy cooking."

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:05.020
Drucker smiled meekly.

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:06.860
"I do you think may
be on to something,"

